{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332893749/1930071901/0346.xml":{"full_text":"Cthp Iroumsuflle HeralO\nEstablished July 4, 1892\nEntered as second-class matter In the Postoffice,\nBrownsville Texas.\nTHE BROWNSVILLE HERALD PUBLISHING\nCOMPANY\nSubscription Rates\u2014DafTj and Sunday (7 issues)\nOne Year *9.00\n81x Months *4.50\nThree Months *2.25\nOne Month 75\nMEMBER OF THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe Associated Press is exclusively entitled to the use\nfor publication of all news dispatches credited to it or\nnet otherwise credited In this paper, and also the\nlocal news published herein\nTEXAS DAILY PRESS LEAGUE\nNational Advertising Representatives\nDallas Texas 512 Mercantile Bank Building\nKansas City Mo\u201e 306 Coca-Cola Building.\nChicago. 111. Association Building.\nNew York 350 Madison Avenue\nSt Louis 502 Star Building\nLos Angeles Cal.. Room 1015 New Orpheum Bldg\n84* S Broadway\nSan Francisco Cal 318 Kohl Building\nHARLINGEN OF* .CE\nArcadia Theater Building Phone 1020\nSpeaking of the Grundy Tariff\nAct\nrYes, speaking of the Grundy tariff act, now effec\ntive, May exports of the United States are Indicated\nIn a bulletin by the commerce department to have de\nclined more to North American countries than to any\nother part of the globe. Drop in import trade for\nP'ay was most serious in shipments from Asia, which\namounted to 350,000039 lers than imports frcm there\nin Mav. Arrcrrlre is a g-eat wheat producing\nT t uying W st from A~ce*it!ne. The\nei by i 'a iff on\ntw re t.ie hr, f;t to him? He has a sur\nplus to sell. This surplus must be sold to nations\nabroad.\nNow the peoples cf these foreign nations are adopt\ning a new policy: they a.e buying wheat and other\nf ;ffs from the r.sMons where they sell their\nr. it-, -Hired wares.\n\u2018.nbor is facing readjustment ordeal.\nV. tv i.it.e is an adjustment, so-called, there is a\n1 n of Red intrigue and propaganda. It comes\n.-jrv*'- i.om individuals who have lost their heads.\nA 1 .s easily handled. He can be snuffed out as\na \u00bbc ,v violator. In Texas the venerable document\nknow n as the constitution provides that taxation shall\nbe equal and uniform. There is a primary campaign\nnearing its close. Candidates for office avoid dis\ncussion of this mandat y provision as timid people\navoid a smallpox infected house or locality. Why not\ninvestigate the records and the platforms of indi\nviduals who are seeking place under the Big\nCome next winter as the makers of the taxation laws\nof this commonwealth?\nLamb County Ha* Big Place On\nTexa* Map\nTurn from the practical politicians and their mur\nir.erings and their grumblings to Lamb county in the\nImperial state of Texas for a close-up. Lamp county\nIs in the Texas Panhandle, near the New Mexico state\nline. A correspondent writes that Lamb has set a\nt record for all other communities to shoot at in the\n1930 census competition. There is a substantial rea\nson for it. Lamb county has a 1930 population given\nas 17,440. or an increase of 1396 per cent in ten years.\nWhen the census was last taken Lamb county had a\npopulation of 1175.\nHall county has a population of 16.961. or an in\ncrease of 52 per cent. Floyd has a population of 12,408,\nor a 27 per cent increase. There is another side to\nthe story. Franklin county shows a decrease of 811,\nHopkins a decrease of 9393. Morris county a decrease\nof 263. Red River county a decrease of 4907, and Titus\ncounty a decease of 2128. There are thousands of\nEast Texans in the Panhandle and plains section of\nthe commonwealth. Why did they jump from the\neast to the west? Well, out In the west there was\ncheap land for the landless. Now there Is cheap land\neverywhere.\nLower Level for Farm Wages\nA two per cent, decline in farm wages is reported\nby the federal agriculture department from April 1\nto July 1 as against the usual seasonal farm wage\nadvance of six per cent for the period. The report\nattributed the recession to a decline in business activ\nity with a resulting increase in industrial unemploy\nment. For a period of five years Col. Arthur Brisbane\ndaily told the readers of his newspapers that pros\nperity would be continuous through all the coming\nyears, as the secret had been discovered at last and\nhis dally warning to the aforesaid readers, \"Don\u2019t\nsell America short,\" was taken by thousands In the\nAmerican provinces, far, far from Wall street and the\nwildest era of gambling in the history of the world\ncontinued until crash followed crash in the fall and\nwinter of 1929-1930.\nDuring these marvelous prosperity years President\nCoolidge backed up the advice given by the news\npaper colonel, and when Coolidge went out and Hoo\nver came in the#famous financial expert of the Ameri\ncan world joined the Brisbane chorus and blamed the\nfederal reserve bank when the rumblings began for\nhigh price call money when cheap money was the\ndemand of those who were playing the royal game\nof getting rich quick in this famous financial center\nof the western world. This was the injunction of a\nfamous American gambler of the 90\u2019s, \"Never place\nyour money on another man\u2019s game.\"\nIn the gTeat university of Experience men and\nwomen are educated. They never take the advice of\nthose who had their fingers scorched and their wal-\nlets flattened In that game called chance with Dame 1\nFortune as the fairy goddess. Now the wise ones are\ntelling how it happened. They will be telling It until j\nthe return of prosperity\u2014Prosperity spelled with a\ncapital P. And then a majority of the suckers will\nbite again.\nMark Traffic Lanes on The\nProgram\nState Highway Engineer Gib Guchrist has let it be\nknown that plans for 40-foot super-road beds, with\nfour marked traffic lar.rs, are being carried forward\nby the department for hi?hways of Terras carrying a\ntraffic load of more than 4000 vehicles per day on an\naverage count over 12 months period. Highway No.\n1 between rallas and Port Worth in Tarrant county\nt'-\" r~r* to be with the four t-affl'* tones.\nTn wh'n 4o_f*v>* hedo\nOOl1'***\n~<9 j O') f J*1 y fir*/\"? WT*3U&n\n1 >-v/\\ \u2019**!oc T n r4 oe {*r*\u00bb*n\n{w) t V'\u00ab tvr,nr* ra*^4,\nt*? V\u2019hv build for todev end let 1*\n\"0 rt that0\nDry A<*t Repeal On\nT*-*\nrr:,\u00bb-ef!vt*<'*s* has an crqanbri\u2018en kr.~wn as the\nConstitutional Liberty League. It has filed at the\n\"\u2018ate horse a rVrrr1-:-i re*'t'~n containing the\nrequisite number cf r\u2018 thus injuring place\nment on t!v\u00bb bai't at f. c>'\".cn cf the qreoticn\nwhether fhe state n enforcement act shall\nbe repealed. Only f?M r'\u2014 cr were necessary, but\nthe petition certains 15CM. Massachusetts Is the\nheme state cf Calvin Coclidne, master of literature.\nIs he a reoe-\u2019c*. a r'-iger or a staunch advocate of\nthe noble experiment?\n______________\nAnother Ecost for U. Permanent\nFund\nAward of 84 leases to high bidders has been made. J\nThe 84 leases include 50.960 acres of University of\nTexas land in Andrews. Ward and Winkler counties\nand brought into the University of Texas permanent\nfund $1,134,180, totaling $15,000,000. Now is the time\nto throw all the shacks on the campus into the river\nbottom. Make Texas university the first of its kind\nin the American commonwealth.\nFess Is the Choice of Hoover\nSen. Simeon D Fess of Ohio, malority whip of the\nupper chamber of congress. Is said to be the Hoover t\nchoice for the chairmanship of the national repub\nlican committee.\nSen. Fess is an ultra-pro. a strong party man. never\nscratches a republican ticket, never bolts a party de\ncree and is for his organization right or wrong. He is\nsaid to be a man of no mean ability, and enjoys the\nrespect of his fellow senators, regardless of party.\nIn other words. Simeon D. Fess of Ohio stands\nwithout being hitched. His party guide book is his\nconscience. He Is a deeply religious man. and the\ngospel of republicanism, night and day and all the\nl time. Is the gospel that directs his movements and\nhis votes.\nIt is Elated for Cal. Claudius Hustot to retire to\nprivate life following decisive action by the senate on\nI the London naval peace pact which is the nasty row\nuppermost at present on the banks of the Potomac.\n\nPopulation of Pennsylvania\nCensus officials indicate a new population for\nPennsylvania at slightly less than 9.900.000, or an\nincrease Insufficient to preserve for the state the pres\nent 36 members In the house of representatives. To be\nexplicit. Napoleon Grundy and his crew are going\nto lose a congressman when the new apportionment I\nis made. Texas may gain two and perhaps three\nOn with the flight.\n\nOur Boarding House By Ahern\nw\nAiisTaH /UVBRose/aHsHo^ I.ytT THanJ ks For pressiaJoj up\nWisH AM colu-p wear \u00a3\u00a7i|f Mv/ wardrobe oasom\nAoE ALT CLOTHES AS TAKE -THIS YeM AMD GEY*\nWELL AS VoT Po VAS VOURSELF A Gold YocYH\nU suH lak ah was W^CALLJ?e ata^i amd\nYellim\u2019 yh? Folks HeaH\u2014 lELL\nAM SAVS PAY MiSYAM r A MALI- Hour\nAMBROSE MUSY HAB YH\u2019 5p(GCOY J AY YHE CAFE LIDO*\nYo YrT FoumYAimI OR VodTH 5^ rflERE\u2019Is' 7\nLocked up i*i His safe1.\u2014 dagger /d vqlJr\n*Jo FboLiAi^-^; evesT cHeR( T\nSunday School Lesson\n\nLeader, Liberator, and Lawgiver\nText: Exod. 3:1-12\nNew 1.1 :s i: .3. tr.? fiocl; of Jeth\nhis father in law. the priest of\nMidiar: and he led the flock to the\nLacK side of the desert, and came\nto the mountain oi G^d, even to\nHorei).\nAnd the an^el of the Lord ap\npeared unto him in a flame of fire\nout of the midst of a bush: and he\nlooked, end behold, the bush burned\nwith fire, and the bush was not con\nsumed.\nAnd Moses said. I will now turn\naside, and see this great sight, why\nthe bush is not burnt.\nAnd when the Lord saw that he\nturned aside to see, God called unto\nhim out of the midst cf the bush,\nand said. Moses, Moses. And he\nsaid. Here am I.\nAnd he said. Draw not nigh hith\ner: put o.f thy shoes frem off thy\nfeet: for the place whereon thou\nstandest is holy ground.\nMoreover he said, I am the God\nof thy father, the God of Abraham,\nthe God of Isaac, and the God of\nJacob. And Moses hid his face: for\nhe was afraid to look upon God.\nAnd the Lord said, I have surely\nseen the affliction of my people\ni wh'ch are in Egypt, and have heard\n\u25a0*>eir c.y by reason of their task\na..tc:s; for I know theu- sorrows.;\nAnd I a in come down to delivei\nm out of .tad of the Egyp\nans. and to b.urg them up out cl\n.hat land unto a good land and a\nlarge, unto a land flowing with\nmilk and honey; unto the place ol\nthe Canaanites, and the Hittites. anc\nthe Amorites, and the Pemzites\nand the Hivites, and the Jebusites\nNow' therefore, behold the cry ol\nthe children of Israel is come untc\nme: and I have also seen the op\npression wherewith the Egyptian!\noppress them.\nCome now therefore, and I will\nsend thee unto Pharaoh, that thor\nmayest bring forth my people th<\nchildren of Israel out of Egypt.\nAnd Mf-ses said unto God. Whc\nam I. that I should go unto Phar\naoh, and that I should bring forti;\nthe children of Israel out of Egypt:\nAnd he said. Certainly I will b<\nwith thee: and this shall be a toker\nunto thee, that I have sent thee\nWhen thou hast brought forth the\npeople out of Egypt, ye shall serve\nGod upon this mountain.\nBY WM. E. GILROY, D. D.\nEditor of the Congregationaiist\nThe three-fold title of our les\nson describes one of the great he\nroic figures of lustoiy\u2014a man\nwhom the whole world has united\nwith the Jewish race in revering\nfor his supermacy.\nThe story of Moses is so pictur\nesque and romantic that the little\nchild may thrill to It. The picture\nof the babe abandoned in the ark\nof bullrushes, and of the adopted\nsen of Pharoh's daughter in honor\nand distinction in the palace com\ning to the consciousness of his one\nness with his people. Is such as to\nentrance the child and to inspire\nflaming youth. And at the same\ntime the strength and power of his\nleader ship in revolt and the ca\npacity and vision of Moses as a law\ngiver make him a figure whom the\nworlds great leaders may revere,\nand to whom they have, as a mat\nter of fact, always given their great\nadmiration.\nFelt a Devine Call\nAs in the case of Abraham, the\ncheif Interest in Moses is. after all,\nthe religious interest. He was a\nman with a sense of the devine\ncall, responsive to spiritual emo\ntions and incentives, a thoughtful\nman, like all thoughtful men feel\ning his own weakness and inade\nquacies in relation to the wor.d of\nhope and aspiration that opened\nbefor him and a man evidently of\nlimited power of verbal expression\nas so many men of action have of\nten been. The greatness of Moses\nwas that in his weakness he was\ncapable of becoming a medium of\ndivine strength. In his humility he\ncould so devote himself to a cause\nthat the cause gave him courage\nand power.\nDeepest of all in the man was\nthe moral vision that created his\nsympathy, his love for his own peo\nple, and his intense championmg\nof them against wrong. The task\nof freeing that people from their\nstrong and powerful oppressors, and\nof leading them forth, surely must\nhave seemed to h\u2019m hopeless had\nit not been for a deep sense in his\nsoul that the man of spiritual cou\nrage must attempt the thing that\nis given him to do, leaving the rest\nto a power greater than himself.\nAbove Self-Interest\nMoses stands not only as a great\nfigure in himself, but as the finest\nsymbol of the liberator\u2014 the man\nwho lives above the plane of self\ninterest, whose purposes in life are\naltogether directed toward higher\nends than his own aggrandizement\nor his own safety. It is such men\nthat give one faith to believe in\nthe reality of the divine In human\nlife.\nIt is in the contrast with such\nmen with self-seekers, and with\neven the learned and great whose\nlearning and greatness are exer\ncised almost wholly for lesser ends\nthat one percieves the meaning of\ngoodness and integrity and devo\ntion to righteous ends. Car. one\ndoubt that one finds in such men\nthe evidence of something that\ntranscends human experience on\nits ordinary levels? Can one ques\ntion the reality of what we call\nthe higher life in man?\nIt is true that we may still re\ngard that life as human as It has\nbeen encompassed in human ex\nperience. but it is not the differ\nence between men to be found in\nthe measure in which with the\ngift of human life they have par\ntaken of the deeper moral and\nspiritual powers that are as real\nin the universe as ite sun and it;\nstars.\nThe Need for Faith\nMoses stands as the great ex\nample of what men can really dc\nwho act in faith and in couragi\nwhen the way is clear. Few mer\nwho are worthy for great task:\nfeel their worthiness. The commoi\nexperience of those who have ac\nhieved great things in moral an<\nspiritual ways is more like this ex\nperience of Mcses. They ask \"Wh<\nam I that I should go?\" And thi\nstrength of their accomplishmen\nhas as its secret the strength tha\nthey find in consecration to thei:\ntask. The presence of the powe:\nthat urges them becomes more man\nHeat in their souls, and they g(\nto resist oppression, to overthrov\nwrong, and to achieve the feat;\nof freedom with the message o\nGod ringing in their souls.\nWEATHER SUMMARY\nThe weather continued fair t<\nclear and settled practical\u2019.:\nj hroughout the country east of thi\nRocky Mountains, but became un\nsettled and rained over the Rock;\nMountain states since last report\nTemperatures also continued sea\n.'enable to above normal practical!:\nthroughout the United Stattes.\nBULLETIN\nFirst figures, lowest temperatur\n.ast night; second highest yester\nday; third, wind velocity at 8 a m\nfourth, precipitation tt. last 2\nhours.\nAbilene 76 98 ,0i\nAmarillo. 66 96 .01\nAtlanta 72 86 .01\nAustin 76 98 .01\nBoise 50 88 .01\nBoston 74 94 .01\nBROWNSVILLE- 77 94 .01\nCalgary 50.II\nChicago 78 98 TO .0\nCleveland 